We study the problem of capacity planning in service systems in which the system operator does not have direct control over which order a server to provide service or not and which service region a server should reposition. In traditional service systems such as call centers and hospitals, servers are stationed at designated locations and follow prescribed rules; the system operator determine the number of servers with the goal to balance operational cost and service quality~\citep[e.g.,][]{gans2003telephone, wang2023simulation}. By contrast, we consider modern \textit{on-demand} service systems where servers strategically decide whether to accept assigned orders and where to reposition after completing a service (e.g., ride-hailing and meal-delivery platforms). In such a setting, the operator determines not only staffing levels but also spatially differentiated compensation structures while minimizing the labor cost and also ensuring the service coverage. Given the set of route-specific compensation, the staffed $N$ servers circulate through the service regions 